metadata.name: RAUSCH #49
metadata.description:
RAUSCH is a series of generative artworks that explore imaginary digital architectures. 

This series challenges traditional notions of architectural representation and raises important questions about the role of resolution in design. Just as the pixel resolution of an image affects its perceived quality, the resolution of an architectural space can affect its qualities and livability. By embracing digital variation through codes, this series explores the interplay between abstract and concrete space through multiple resolutions. 

RAUSCH is inspired by the feeling of being overwhelmed by complex, chaotic and messy sensations, and aims to engage the viewer through a sense of wonder, disorientation, and awe.

Released on the occasion of Companions of Code, a group exhibition by VerticalCrypto Art at The NFT Gallery in London. 
Curated by Micol Ap. Exhibition 10-24 February 2023

metadata.name: Flume #276
metadata.description:
Flume are infinitely flowing digital bodies of water.
The flow of Flumes can range from slow and gentle, creating small ripples and eddies, to fast and turbulent, carving its way through the inner workings of your computer screen. 
The color, clarity, and viscosity of the water can also vary.

This is the culmination of my collection Flume, an exploration into On-Chain art on Ethereum, https://etherscan.io/address/0x1fa23513825f952afca07a603ac3f312ebee4ca9

These pieces were all created in p5js.

- Andrew

metadata.name: contrapuntos #640
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-RodrÃ­guez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.

metadata.name: Freaky Future #17
metadata.description:
///////// A DYSTOPIC IMMERSIVE EXPERIENCE //////////

Freaky Future is a collection of 4004 randomly generated & unique life forms. 
FF is a Sci-Fi story, part of this story is written in the names of the assets. So pay attention to this!
Made from 119 unique hand drawn assets.
The result comes from mixing 14 png layers.-

created by Gualicho and developed by LaureanO

It's the year 4004, life on our planet is connected to a virtual metaverse. Nobody knows what happened but the system collapsed and resulted in the deconstruction of all life forms. Humans, machines and animals randomly merged together, as a new species arose.
PLANET EARTH NOW HAS A SECOND CHANCE TO EVOLVE.


/ / / / / / JOIN THE FREAKS / / / / / /
www.freakyfuture.wtf


Mint will be open for 7 days, after that, if there is a remain, will be burn

metadata.name: SquarePlus #124
metadata.description:
A study of basic shapes ended up with Squares or Pluses. Each layer has a different color code along with a point-related rotation and scale which result in an elegant composition.

Press s in live mode to download.

Download a higher resolution by adding to the URL:
&density=2 / &density=3 / &density=4

Lammetje Februari 2023

metadata.name: DEGREES OF FREEDOM #16
metadata.description:
Forms constricted to a plane, yearning to be free. Multitudes of expression, endless possibilities of shapes, the inevitable hissing rising from the dreaded empty page.

This piece is inspired by the Futurists' concept of 'universal dynamism' - the idea that separations between objects and their contexts are an illusion and time makes any distinctions meaningless. It tries to capture the expressivity of the moving object along all its potential vectors.

This piece evolved from my #genuary piece for 'Minimalism' (which was even then more surrealism than anything else). DEGREES OF FREEDOM is minted as part of #genuary32nd.

Press 'S' to take a screenshot. Recommended resolution: 2400 x 3000 pixels.
Written in JavaScript without libraries, February 2023.

metadata.name: NYC-80 #25
metadata.description:
Even if this work was intended as an abstract study, the crowded, rhythmically repeating structures are reminiscent of the monumental, anonymous appearance of some large cities.
The appearance is determined by naive strong strokes and simple forms that give the picture a strong and self-confident expressiveness reminiscent of the art of the New York art scene of the 80s. The surfaces are deliberately not layered, in order to underline the impenetrability, but also to preserve the abstract painterly element.
